¿	Safety and Engineering Controls

The Plant compiles and maintains the following up-to-date safety information related to aqueous ammonia, processes, and equipment: 

¿	Material Safety Data Sheet for aqueous ammonia (CAS No. 1336-21-6) which will meet the requirements of 29 CFR 1910.1200(g); 

¿	Maximum intended inventory of equipment in which the regulated substances are stored or processed which will be a 40,000 gallon AST; 

¿	Safe upper and lower temperatures, pressures, flows, and compositions; 

¿	Equipment specifications; and 

¿	Codes and standards used to design, build, and operate the process. 

The Plant will ensure that the process is designed in compliance with recognized and generally accepted good engineering practices and be in compliance with applicable federal and state regulations that address industry-specific safe design or with industry-specific design codes and standards.  Also, the Plant will update the safety information if a major change occurs that makes the information inaccurate.

(E)).  The Contingency Plan was developed based on requirements found in 40 CFR 262.34(a)(4); 40 CFR 265 Subpart D; the Code of Maryland Regulations (COMAR) 26.13.05.02 General Facility Standards; COMAR 26.13.05.03 Preparedness and Prevention; and COMAR 26.13.05.04 Contingency Plan and Emergency Procedures.  Also included in the Contingency Plan are additional requirements outlined in 40 CFR 262.34(d)(5)(i).
As part of preparing the Contingency Plan, the Plant also developed an Emergency Response and Disaster Control Plan that describes the actions that will be taken in the case of small or large fires, explosions, sudden or non-sudden chemical releases, natural events, public hazards (i.e., bomb threats, riots, etc.) or oil spills related to daily operations at the Plant.  The Contingency Plan mirrors the Emergency Response and Disaster Control Plan in terms of response method and response team organization to ensure consistency between the two Plans.   

Pursuant to the requirements of the December 5, 2008 amendments to Title 40 of the Code of Federal Regulations Part 112 (40 CFR 112), as well as the Code of Maryland Regulations (COMAR) 26.10.01 governing oil pollution and tank management rules, the Plant has developed and implemented a SPCC Plan.   The SPCC Plan was prepared to address federal and state requirements for response to and prevention of spills.  Applicable regulations regarding spill prevention, reporting, and response are:
¿	40 CFR 112 - Environmental Protection Agency Regulations on Oil Pollution Prevention;
¿	40 CFR 110 - Discharge of Oil;
¿	40 CFR 117 and 40 CFR 302.4 - Determination of Reportable Quantities for Hazardous Substances;
¿	40 CFR 302 - Designation, Reportable Quantities and Notification;
¿	40 CFR 300 - National Oil and Hazardous Substances Pollution Contingency Plan; 
¿	40 CFR 355 - Emergency Planning and Notification; and 
¿	COMAR 26.10.01.12 - Requirements for Above-Ground Oil Storage Facilities
